% v2-final τ²-bench retail subsection. n=100 numbers populated.
% Headline: pull dominates intercept under matched payload.

\subsubsection{Reader-side architecture head-to-head: pull vs.\
intercept on $\tau^2$-bench retail}
\label{sec:eval:results:retail-intercept}

\paragraph{Question.}
\S\ref{sec:eval:results:travelplanner-isolation} established that the
pull \emph{channel} is load-bearing within ET-MCP under matched
payload, on TravelPlanner.  Two open questions remain.  \emph{(i)}~Does
the finding generalize beyond TravelPlanner---in particular, to a
public, peer-reviewed benchmark whose scorer is state-validated rather
than retrieval-redundancy-based?  \emph{(ii)}~Holding the underlying
event store, writer policy, and payload constant, does the
\emph{reader-side architecture}---agent-as-reader vs.\ framework-as-
reader---move the headline metric?  We answer both with a controlled
head-to-head on $\tau^2$-bench retail.

\paragraph{Benchmark.}
$\tau^2$-bench~\cite{tau2bench2025} (Sierra Research) is a
state-validated conversational agent benchmark: each trial passes
only if its final database state matches the state produced by
replaying the task's reference action sequence.  Redundant or
wrong-state write calls register as scoring failures directly.  The
official headline metric is pass$^k$: the fraction of tasks where
\emph{all} $k$ independent trials succeed---a reliability metric that
rewards cross-trial coordination intrinsically when peer state can be
shared.  We evaluate the retail domain at pass$^2$ as the workshop
audience's primary reliability surface, and report pass$^1$ for
single-trial comparison.

\paragraph{Harness.}
$\tau^2$-bench's bundled litellm-based pipeline produces malformed
Anthropic-API message histories on multi-turn retail tasks, yielding
$\geq 30\%$ silent infra-error rates with the stock
\texttt{LLMAgent} on Anthropic Haiku in our pilot measurements (a
failure class consistent with multiple open BerriAI/litellm
issues~\cite{litellmissue12404,litellmissue15322}).  We evaluate
through a $\sim$700-line Anthropic-native harness that re-uses
$\tau^2$'s domain database, tools, task definitions, and DB-hash
reward function but constructs its conversation state directly
against the Anthropic Messages API.  Zero infra errors at 600
trials.  The harness is released alongside the paper.

\paragraph{Protocols.}
Three protocols share an identical writer side: at the close of any
trial that ended with reward $<\!1$, the final $k=3$ tool calls of
that trial are recorded as \textsc{failed\_trial\_action} events in
the task-scoped store.  ($k{=}3$ is a causal-attribution heuristic
discussed in \S\ref{sec:discussion:writer}; an all-actions writer
overattributes causality and degrades both pull and intercept,
matching our pilot-study finding.)  The protocols differ only in the
reader interface:

\begin{description}
\item[\texttt{no\_coord}.] No cross-trial state.  Each trial is
  independent; the trace store is unused.  Baseline.
\item[\texttt{pull}.] Agent-as-reader.  At trial start, the store is
  summarized into a \texttt{<peer\_warnings>} block prepended to the
  agent's system prompt.  No per-turn overhead beyond a longer
  system prompt; the agent decides how to weigh the warnings against
  the current state.
\item[\texttt{intercept}.] Framework-as-reader.  No system-prompt
  augmentation; the agent's tool surface is unchanged.  When the
  agent calls a tool whose (name, arguments) appears in the store as
  a \textsc{failed\_trial\_action} from a peer trial, the
  orchestrator prepends a structured \texttt{[PEER-WARNING]} block
  to the tool's response before returning it to the agent.
\end{description}

Pull and intercept share the writer policy, the event store, and the
MCP-conformant transport (\S\ref{sec:architecture}).  They differ
only in the reader interface.  This is the matched-payload
controlled comparison: any pass$^k$ difference between pull and
intercept must be attributed to the reader-side architecture, not
to which events are available.

\paragraph{Setup.}
We sampled 100 tasks from $\tau^2$-bench retail (seed 42),
$\times$ 3 protocols $\times$ 2 trials $=$ 600 trials.  Both the
assistant and the simulated user are Claude Haiku 4.5
(\texttt{claude-haiku-4-5}), temperature 0, with a 20 assistant-turn
budget per trial.  The task-scoped store is shared across the 2
trials of a task within a protocol cell and reset between cells.

\paragraph{Headline result.}
Table~\ref{tab:tau2retail:headline} reports cell-level metrics;
Table~\ref{tab:tau2retail:pairwise} reports paired comparisons
against \texttt{no\_coord} and the intercept-vs-pull contrast.

