\paragraph{Reader architecture is load-bearing under matched payload.}
The intercept-vs-pull comparison is the architectural head-to-head:
identical writer, identical event store, identical payload, the only
difference is who is the active reader.  Pull dominates intercept by
$+0.18$ Cliff's $\delta$ on pass$^1$ (sign-test $p=0.004$
uncorrected; 27 task-level losses for intercept against 9 wins) and
by $+0.11$ on pass$^2$ ($p=0.043$).  Cell-level effects are
substantial: pull's pass$^1$ is $+18$\,pp absolute over intercept's
($0.62$ vs.\ $0.44$).  Under Holm-Bonferroni correction across the
four vs.-no\_coord tests, no individual contrast reaches $p<0.05$
(the closest is intercept-vs-no\_coord on pass$^1$, $p_{\textrm{Holm}}{=}0.44$),
reflecting the high tie rate of binary pass$^k$ comparisons; the
matched-payload head-to-head sidesteps this because pull and
intercept differ on far more tasks than either differs from
no\_coord.  We treat the head-to-head contrast as the architectural
claim and the vs.-no\_coord contrasts as descriptive cell-level
context.

\paragraph{Pull generalizes; intercept does not improve over no
coordination.}
Pull's pass$^k$ lift over \texttt{no\_coord} ($+8$\,pp pass$^1$,
$+6$\,pp pass$^2$) is directional but not significant at $n{=}100$;
the picture remains consistent with the
\S\ref{sec:eval:results:travelplanner-isolation} within-system
finding that the pull channel is the load-bearing component.
Intercept, in contrast, underperforms \texttt{no\_coord} on
\emph{both} metrics ($-10$\,pp pass$^1$, $-5$\,pp pass$^2$;
non-significant directionally), so the framework-side reader is not
recovering the architectural benefit observed within-system.

\paragraph{Mechanistic interpretation.}
The intercept store accumulates a mean of $2.77$
\textsc{failed\_trial\_action} events per trial (max $8$).  Each
matching tool call in a subsequent trial fires a separate
\texttt{[PEER-WARNING]} block on the tool response.  The agent
receives warnings at the moment of the relevant call but cannot
weigh them globally against the current state---some matched tool
calls may have legitimately succeeded in past trials and failed for
reasons unrelated to the tool arguments (e.g., upstream state
mutation).  Pull's single trial-start summary lets the agent
exercise judgment: read once, contextualize, and choose when to
defer to the warning.  At the scale we test, the agent's
discrimination dominates the framework's coverage.  This is the
inverse of the production-stack intuition---that framework
mediation improves on agent self-management---and suggests
coordination semantics are not symmetric with the security/blocking
semantics that motivate production hook surfaces.

\paragraph{Cost.}
All three cells use comparable input-token budgets ($75.7$K--$77.2$K
mean, intercept lowest by $2$\%).  The lift from pull is therefore a
strict architectural win, not a cost-quality tradeoff.

\paragraph{Limitations.}
The reader-side architecture finding holds at $n{=}100$ tasks on a
single retail domain at a single model checkpoint
(Haiku~4.5, $T{=}0$); cross-domain generalization (airline,
telecom---both have weaker coordination signals in pilot studies)
and cross-model generalization (Sonnet/Opus) are open.  The writer-side
selection policy ($k{=}3$) is fixed and hand-tuned.  Pass$^k$ at
$k>2$ would let us measure whether the architectural gap widens
with retry budget; we leave this to future work.
